stylometry: The trade-off that managers must consider when dealing with waiting lines are the costs associated with providing more service, and the "cost" of customer satisfaction. It is easy to figure out the costs of providing more service (example, hiring another employee to make service quicker), but it is very difficult to calculate the costs of making your customers happy. If the time to wait is too long, customers may get angry and not come back to the store, restaurant, ect. Managers must decide if the cost of hiring another employee is less than the revenue that that customer would bring in. The objective is to minimize costs while mainting good customer satifaction so your customers do not have to wait very long.
